                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">This is mostly spell propositioning here, with a few questions/concerns about them (in italics) as they exist currently, so I'll try to stick to that general theme.  I'm going to be mirroring Ravvenn somewhat (sorry!), but I'll try not to repeat her verbatim. <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" />  Also, any spell coded in <span style="color: red">red</span> will be the spell's LINE, not the individual one.  <span style="color: blue">Blues</span> are the individual spell itself.
<br />

<br />
My thoughts on spell utility are listed as an unordered list; since the game's spell engine apparently supports melee boosts outside of stats and haste (ie - critical hits and whatnot), I'm hoping for some really cool stuff for us come Gates of Discord (bumping critical hit chances, as an example). <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />  *gets a wine bottle and several glasses for making a toast to said hoping for anyone who wants to join in*  And without further ado, I'll start with spell lines.
<br />

<br />
<span style="color: red">Cripple</span>: Basically I was thinking that this line could gain a stacking ability, up to a certain degree.  I'm not certain how this could be coded, if it's even possible because of how DoT stacking works, but I have never casted Cripple since about level 55.  I've been 56+ for about a year now, if that's saying something.  <span style="font-style: italic">As such, mostly I'm curious about the intended usage of this spell line, since it doesn't appear to change NPC damage or avoidance on a very noticeable scale.</span>
<br />

<br />
- add "to hit decrease" and/or to Cripple line
<br />
- add "damage decrease" to -str line (Insipid Weakness, etc.)
<br />

<br />
<span style="color: red">Strangle/Asphyxiate</span>: I use our DoTs, sure, but not always, as in some cases we're too busy with crowd control to worry about maintaining a DoT (Rathe, for instance). <span style="font-style: italic">Was this mostly for soloing or basic exp-group support?</span>  If I were to change it, or give my $0.02 (heheharhar), I would say the following: nerf the stat debuffs (add one to Strangle) and allow the stat debuffs to stack; 10 enchanters stacking Strangle, for instance, I don't see happening.  I've never even seen 10 Enchanters on a raid, let alone together in the same area, so I'm not thinking we'll have -200 str/agi/ac on an NPC.  More like 120, and even still that would only be a boss mob or high HP yard trash which could be stat-buffed beyond that to begin with.  (Or a special anti-statlower flag coded; either or would work really.)
<br />

<br />
<span style="color: red">Torment of Argli</span>: I really don't use this much, even on casting NPCs.  <span style="font-style: italic">What is the purpose of this?</span>
<br />
- add a very minor negative foci (2%?) to the NPC (spell and dot damage) and let that stack; in other words, we're harming their casting effectiveness.  For the sake of numbers: Quarm's 3k AE would require 10 Enchanters to lower it to 2400, assuming AE's are affected by such foci.  I myself don't know of any guilds using that many Enchanters in Time (do any?), but anything's possible I suppose...
<br />

<br />
<span style="color: red">Mana Sieve/Theft of Thought</span>: Suggestions only.  Enough said. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />  Also a question: <span style="font-style: italic">Is Theft of Thought supposed to be an upgrade for Mana Sieve, even with a much higher recast?</span>
<br />
- upgrades!  (meaning more higher-level spells for each, not buffing)
<br />
- fixing the issue where Theft of Thought <span style="font-weight: bold">loses</span> effectiveness (less mana gained) as an NPC level increases, even if it's the same class of NPC
<br />

<br />
<span style="color: red">Scryer's/Wandering</span>: <span style="font-style: italic">Are these affected by DoT foci</span> (DoT-damage and duration boosting)?  If not, allowing them to be such would <span style="font-weight: bold">greatly</span> make them very useful Enchanter spells indeed.
<br />

<br />
<span style="color: red">Illusions</span>: At this point in the game, <span style="font-style: italic">factions seem to be rather a farce</span>.  For example: NPCs on a faction that already starts KOS to everyone, has further reductions to it and no raising methods for it whatsoever, as far as anyone knows (ie - the Trakanon faction in Sebilis).  As such, in several cases (the entire Planes of Power expansion, more or less, and a good majority of Luclin and Kunark for that matter; old-world and Velious are about the only exceptions) they're pointless to even worry about.  I recognize that in the case of the racial ones, they're fun to use and in some cases are mandatory for our epic quest (going to Neriak if you're a high-elf and not altered factions, same with Qeynos).
<br />

<br />
<span style="color: red">Alliance</span>:  I'll be posting a "game mechanic" type of deal later, where factions will be included, so I won't say anything here.
<br />

<br />
<span style="color: red">Memory Blur</span>:  <span style="font-style: italic">A FAILURE MESSAGE</span>.  Period.  I would love to know if it didn't work, the same as melees with using Taunt.  It would also show us if well and truly Reoccurring Amnesia is working or not. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />  I haven't decided if this line needs a fundamental change or not besides a set %age to work or not.  I will say this though: <span style="font-style: italic">the AE versions (Mind Wipe in particular) seem to be <span style="font-weight: bold">much</span> more successful than the considerably higher-levelled, <span style="font-weight: bold">single</span> target Memory Flux, which costs about three times the mana</span>.  Something to think about.
<br />

<br />
Now, before I go into individual spells (some of which will fall into the following question are listed below), I must ask this:  <span style="font-style: italic">Why are only one type of a spell created?</span>  Largarn's Lamentation and Curse of the Simple Mind are my prime examples of this.  Why were they created, and why were they not "evolved" or simply scrapped?  KEI (and obviously Bind Affinity) was a special case when it was first created (it also got an upgrade with PoP), as it was a buff/debuff consolidation; the above-mentioned spells don't qualify there.  Mostly I want to ask the dev team <span style="font-style: italic">to recognize the "orphaning" of these types of spells (exclude Sentinel/Sanctuary from that)</span>, of which there exists only one of them, and does something unique relative to every other spell for that class, <span style="font-style: italic">and to act upon them in a beneficial manner</span>, namely give them cause to be utilized either at the level they're given, or given a spell line; SOMETHING!  <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /> I always get the hope there will be a new spell added that will remove this "orphan" tag in an expansion, but I haven't seen it yet.  Call me empathic for the lonely spells. ;/
<br />

<br />
<span style="color: blue">Curse of the Simple Mind</span>: The one spell of its kind, and I don't really use it anymore (and never really did), except to see if maybe it makes caster NPCs easier to manage.  (NO conclusion reached.)  I myself would lean towards the DoT proposal as listed below
<br />
- add upgrades to this spell <span style="font-weight: bold">OR</span> make it a precursor to Torment of Argli; I would lean towards the mana-dot aspect myself, since that's all that's different between this and Argli
<br />
- also add negative spell foci, as described above with the Argli line
<br />

<br />
<span style="color: blue">Largarn's Lamentation</span>: <span style="font-style: italic">Any chance of upgrades to this?</span>  I would propose something very radical here, but I don't feel like getting censured/flamed/etc., so I won't and I'll just talk to other people about it instead before I say anything. <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Possibly more to come (a reply to this post), but I think I've exhausted my brain for now... Happy reading. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
